<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-931-034  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 931 034.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Dec 4 1989 v11 n49 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM study: PCs aid in decision process.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaPlante, Alice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputers in a work group can help managers in the decisionmaking process, according to a study co-sponsored by IBM.andP;  Thegroup in question consisted of 48 users at the CollaborativeManagement Workshop at the University of Arizona at Tucson wherePS/2s were linked together in a local area network (LAN).andP;  Theconference room where these microcomputers were located isspecially designed to enable the users to work together,simultaneously using the same group productivity software that theUniversity of Arizona developed for its own use.andP;  TheCollaborative Management Workshop used software that facilitateselectronic brainstorming, issue analysis, setting priorities,formation of policy and identification of who would be affected bydecisions that the group enacted.andP;  The workshop is available forcorporate use at a rate of $2,000 per day.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (research).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersWork Group ComputingDecision MakingUser StudiesArizona, University of.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>